{
    "ocr_text": "Mr. George C. Roddan, Secretary,
Trades and Labor Council,
514 Humaine St., New Orleans, La.

Dear Sir and Brother:

I want to acknowledge receipt of your favor of November 19,
in which by direction of the Central Trades and Labor Council, you
enclose copy of the report of the Committee appointed by the Council,
to investigate the report of the charges made by Miss Jean Gordon of
New Orleans in a speech which she delivered in Chicago, in which she
charged the Trades and Labor Council and the Louisiana State Federation
of Labor in blocking and thwarting legislation in favor of women and
children.

You will be interested in knowing that I am sending a copy
of this report to the members of the Executive Council of the A. F.
of L. for their information. At the same time I want to express my
appreciation of the full and comprehensive report made upon the subject.

With kind regards, I am,
Fraternally yours,

President
American Federation of Labor.",
    "summary": "The letter acknowledges receipt of a previous communication containing a report regarding accusations made by Miss Jean Gordon against the Trades and Labor Council and the Louisiana State Federation of Labor. The accusations were about blocking legislation favorable to women and children. The letter also mentions sending this report to the Executive Council and expresses appreciation for the comprehensive nature of the report.",
